 1993)|Vitinho]] || || {{subon|85}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Lincoln (footballer, born 2000)|Lincoln]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''28'''||{{flagicon|COL}} [[Orlando Berr\u00edo]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=3|{{flagicon|POR}} [[Jorge Jesus]]\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|[[File:Flamengo vs River Plate 2019-11-23.svg|300px]]\n|valign=\"top\" width=\"50%\"|\n{| style=\"font-size:90%; margin:auto\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n|-\n!width=25| !!width=25|\n|-\n|GK ||'''1''' ||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Franco Armani]]\n|-\n|RB ||'''29'''||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Gonzalo Montiel]]\n|-\n|CB ||'''28'''||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Lucas Mart\u00ednez Quarta]]\n|-\n|CB ||'''22'''||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Javier Pinola]] ([[Captain (association football)|c]])\n|-\n|LB ||'''20'''||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Milton Casco]] || {{yel|29}} || {{suboff|76}}\n|-\n|DM ||'''24'''||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Enzo P\u00e9rez]] || {{yel|70}}\n|-\n|RM ||'''26'''||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Ignacio Fern\u00e1ndez (footballer)|Ignacio Fern\u00e1ndez]] || || {{suboff|68}}\n|-\n|CM ||'''15'''||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Exequiel Palacios]] || {{sent off|0|90+5}}\n|-\n|LM ||'''11'''||{{flagicon|URU}} [[Nicol\u00e1s De La Cruz]]\n|-\n|CF ||'''19'''||{{flagicon|COL}} [[Rafael Santos Borr\u00e9]] || || {{suboff|74}}\n|-\n|CF ||'''7''' ||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Mat\u00edas Su\u00e1rez]] || {{yel|45+1}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Substitutes:'''\n|-\n|GK ||'''14'''||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Germ\u00e1n Lux]]\n|-\n|GK ||'''25'''||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Enrique Bologna]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''2''' ||{{flagicon|PAR}} [[Robert Rojas]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''4''' ||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Fabrizio Angileri]]\n|-\n|DF ||'''6''' ||{{flagicon|CHI}} [[Paulo D\u00edaz]] || || {{subon|76}}\n|-\n|MF ||'''5''' ||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Bruno Zuculini]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''10'''||{{flagicon|COL}} [[Juan Fernando Quintero]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''21'''||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Cristian Ferreira]]\n|-\n|MF ||'''23'''||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Leonardo Ponzio]]\n|-\n|FW ||'''9''' ||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Juli\u00e1n \u00c1lvarez (footballer)|Juli\u00e1n \u00c1lvarez]] || || {{subon|68}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''27'''||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Lucas Pratto]] || || {{subon|74}}\n|-\n|FW ||'''30'''||{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Ignacio Scocco]]\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''Manager:'''\n|-\n|colspan=3|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Marcelo Gallardo]]\n|}\n|}\n\n{| width=100% style=\"font-size:90%\"\n|\n'''[[Assistant referee (association football)|Assistant referees]]:'''<ref name=\"referees\">{{cite news|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/roberto-tobar-es-el-arbitro-designado-para-dirigir-la-final-de-la-conmebol-libertadores|title=Roberto Tobar es el \u00e1rbitro designado para dirigir la final de la CONMEBOL Libertadores|publisher=CONMEBOL|date=12 November 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/sustitucion-de-arbitro-var-de-la-final-de-la-conmebol-libertadores-2019|title=Sustituci\u00f3n de \u00c1rbitro VAR de la final de la CONMEBOL Libertadores 2019|publisher=CONMEBOL|date=19 November 2019|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n<br />Christian Schiemann ([[Football Federation of Chile|Chile]])\n<br />Claudio R\u00edos ([[Football Federation of Chile|Chile]])\n<br />'''[[Assistant referee (association football)#Fourth official|Fourth official]]:'''\n<br />Andr\u00e9s Rojas ([[Colombian Football Federation|Colombia]])\n<br />'''[[Video assistant referee]]:'''\n<br />Esteban Ostojich ([[Uruguayan Football Association|Uruguay]])\n<br />'''[[Video assistant referee#Assistant video assistant referee|Assistant video assistant referees]]:'''\n<br />Piero Maza ([[Football Federation of Chile|Chile]])\n<br />Alexander Guzm\u00e1n ([[Colombian Football Federation|Colombia]])\n<br />[[V\u00edctor Carrillo]] ([[Peruvian Football Federation|Peru]])\n|style=\"width:60%; vertical-align:top;\"|\n'''Match rules'''\n*90 minutes.\n*30 minutes of [[Overtime (sports)#Association football|extra time]] if necessary.\n*[[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|Penalty shoot-out]] if scores still level.\n*Twelve named substitutes.\n*Maximum of three substitutions, with a fourth allowed in extra time.\n|}\n\n==Post-match==\n\nFlamengo won their second Copa Libertadores and earned the right to represent CONMEBOL at the [[2019 FIFA Club World Cup]] in Qatar. Jorge Jesus became the second non-South American manager to win the Copa Libertadores, following [[Mirko Jozi\u0107]]'s 1991 championship for [[Colo-Colo]].<ref>{{cite news |date=23 November 2019 |title=Late goals give Flamengo dramatic Copa Libertadores title |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/soccer/late-goals-give-flamengo-dramatic-copa-libertadores-title/2019/11/23/5a0287fc-0e3e-11ea-8054-289aef6e38a3_story.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> The club went on to clinch the [[2019 Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A]] title a day later after the second-place team was mathematically eliminated from reaching the title.<ref>{{cite news |date=24 November 2019 |title=Flamengo win Brazilian league while celebrating Copa Libertadores title |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/flamengo/story/3997747/flamengo-win-brazilian-league-while-celebrating-copa-libertadores-title |publisher=[[ESPN]] |agency=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref> Flamengo became the first Brazilian club to earn a league and continental [[Double (association football)|double]] since [[Santos FC]] did in 1963. The victory celebrations in Rio de Janeiro attracted tens of thousands of fans as the players rode in an open-top bus, but ended with clashes between [[riot police]] and spectators.<ref>{{cite news |date=24 November 2019 |title=Flamengo clinch double as Rio celebrations are marred by clashes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/nov/24/flameng-ocopa-libertadores-celebrations-clashes-police |work=The Guradian |accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=25 November 2019 |title=Flamengo's Copa Libertadores celebrations end in clashes |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/11869688/flamengos-copa-libertadores-celebrations-end-in-clashes |work=[[Sky Sports]] |accessdate=25 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nFlamengo's two late goals to overturn a 0\u20131 deficit invited comparisons to the [[1999 UEFA Champions League Final]], in which [[Manchester United]] defeated [[Bayern Munich]] in a similar fashion.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20191123-flamengo-overcome-river-plate-2-1-to-win-football-s-copa-libertadores|title=Flamengo lift Copa Libertadores with last-gasp 2-1 win over River Plate|date=23 November 2019|work=France 24}}</ref>\n\n== Broadcasting ==\nIn Brazil, the match was broadcast by [[Rede Globo]] with commentary provided by Luiz Roberto, [[J\u00fanior]] and [[Walter Casagrande]], in addition to [[Fox Sports]] on cable television with commentary provided by Nivaldo Prieto, [[Edmundo]] and Paulo Vinicius Coelho. The broadcast attracted 41.1 million viewers, with almost half of the television sets in Brazil were watching the Globo's broadcast.<ref>Kantar Ibope - [https://www.kantaribopemedia.com/dados-de-audiencia-nas-15-pracas-regulares-com-base-no-ranking-consolidado-2503-a-03032019-3-2-2-3-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2-2/ Dados de audi\u00eancia nas 15 pra\u00e7as regulares com base no ranking consolidado \u2013 18/11 a 24/11/2019]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2019 Copa Sudamericana Final]]\n*[[2020 Recopa Sudamericana]]\n*[[1999 UEFA Champions League Final]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.conmebol.com/es/copa-libertadores-2019 CONMEBOL Libertadores 2019], CONMEBOL\n\n{{2019 in South American football (CONMEBOL)}}\n{{Copa Libertadores seasons}}\n{{Clube de Regatas do Flamengo matches}}\n{{River Plate matches}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Copa Libertadores Final 2019}}\n[[Category:Copa Libertadores Finals|2019]]\n[[Category:2019 Copa Libertadores|*Final]]\n[[Category:November 2019 sports events in South America]]\n[[Category:Clube de Regatas do Flamengo matches]]\n[[Category:River Plate matches]]\n[[Category:2019 in Brazilian football]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 in Argentine football]]\n[[Category:International club association football competitions hosted by Peru]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox football match\n| title              = 2019 Copa Libertadores Final\n| event              = [[2019 Copa Libertadores]]\n| team1              = [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo|Flamengo]]\n| team1association   = {{flagicon|BRA|size=30px}}\n| team1score         = 2\n| team2              = [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]]\n| team2association   = {{flagicon|ARG|size=30px}}\n| team2score         = 1\n| details            =\n| date               = {{Start date|2019|11|23|df=y}}\n| stadium            = [[Estadio Monumental \"U\"|Estadio Monumental]]\n| city               = [[Lima]]\n| man_of_the_match1a = \n| referee            = [[Roberto Tobar]] ([[Football Federation of Chile|Chile]])\n| attendance         = \n| weather            = \n| previous           = [[2018 Copa Libertadores Finals|2018]]\n| next               = ''[[2020 Copa Libertadores Final|2020]]''\n}}\nThe '''2019 Copa Libertadores Final''' decided the winner of the [[2019 Copa Libertadores]]. This was the 60th edition of the [[Copa Libertadores]], the top-tier South American continental club [[Association football|football]] tournament organized by [[CONMEBOL]].<ref name=\"regulations\">{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/sites/default/files/reglamento-conmebol-libertadores-2019-esp.pdf|title=Reglamento CONMEBOL Libertadores 2019|publisher=CONMEBOL|url-status=live|ref={{sfnref|Reglamento}}}}</ref>\n\nThe final was contested between [[Brazilian Football Confederation|Brazilian]] team [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo|Flamengo]] and the [[2018 Copa Libertadores|defending champions]], [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]] from [[Argentine Football Association|Argentina]]. This was the first Copa Libertadores final to be played as a single match at a neutral venue chosen in advance, replacing the previous home-and-away format. The match was played at the [[Estadio Monumental \"U\"|Estadio Monumental]] in [[Lima]], Peru on 23 November 2019.\n\nFlamengo won the match 2\u20131, securing their second tournament title. As champions, they qualified as the CONMEBOL representative at the [[2019 FIFA Club World Cup]] and the [[2020 Recopa Sudamericana]]. They also automatically qualified for the [[2020 Copa Libertadores]] group stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/flamengo-campeon-de-la-conmebol-libertadores-2019-0|title=\u00a1Flamengo campe\u00f3n de la CONMEBOL Libertadores 2019!|publisher=CONMEBOL|date=23 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Team\n!Previous finals appearances (bold indicates winners)\n|-\n|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo|Flamengo]]\n|1 ('''[[1981 Copa Libertadores Finals|1981]]''')\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]]\n|6 ([[1966 Copa Libertadores Finals|1966]], [[1976 Copa Libertadores Finals|1976]], '''[[1986 Copa Libertadores Finals|1986]]''', '''[[1996 Copa Libertadores Finals|1996]]''', '''[[2015 Copa Libertadores Finals|2015]]''', '''[[2018 Copa Libertadores Finals|2018]]''')\n|}\n\n==Venue==\n[[File:Estadio_Monumental_en_la_final_2009.jpg|thumb|[[Estadio Monumental \"U\"|Estadio Monumental]] in [[Lima]], Peru, hosted the final.]]\nIn 2017, CONMEBOL proposed that the Copa Libertadores final should be held as a single match, replacing the existing [[two-legged]] format.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.publimetro.co/co/deportes/2017/10/03/cambios-en-la-copa-libertadores-desde-2019.html|title=As\u00ed cambiar\u00e1 la Copa Libertadores desde el 2019|publisher=publimetro.co|date=3 October 2017}}</ref> On 23 February 2018, CONMEBOL confirmed that the 2019 final onwards would be played as a single match at a venue chosen in advance,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/la-conmebol-libertadores-se-definira-en-final-unica-partir-de-2019-con-mayores-beneficios-los-clubes|title=La CONMEBOL Libertadores se definir\u00e1 en final \u00fanica a partir de 2019 con mayores beneficios a los clubes y la competencia|publisher=CONMEBOL|date=23 February 2018}}</ref> and on 11 June 2018 set the date of the match as 23 November 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eltiempo.com/deportes/futbol-internacional/definida-la-fecha-de-la-final-de-la-copa-conmebol-libertadores-2019-228970|title=Definida la fecha de la final de la Copa Conmebol Libertadores 2019|publisher=[[El Tiempo (Colombia)|El Tiempo]]|date=11 June 2018|language=Spanish}}</ref> On 14 August 2018, CONMEBOL announced that the 2019 final would be played in [[Santiago]], [[Chile]] at the [[Estadio Nacional Julio Mart\u00ednez Pr\u00e1danos|Estadio Nacional]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Hist\u00f3rica decisi\u00f3n: Final \u00danica de la Libertadores 2019 en Santiago y Final \u00danica de la Sudamericana 2019 en Lima |url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/historica-decision-final-unica-de-la-libertadores-2019-en-santiago-y-final-unica-de-la-sudamericana |publisher=CONMEBOL|date=14 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nLarge [[2019 Chilean protests|street protests in Chile]] began on 14 October 2019, involving millions of protestors and resulting in the deaths of at least 24 people.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Esposito |first1=Anthony |title=Human rights abuse accusations proliferate in Chile unrest |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-chile-protests-rights-widerimage/human-rights-abuse-accusations-proliferate-in-chile-unrest-idUSKBN1XP1Z5 |website=Reuters |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=25 November 2019 |date=15 November 2019}}</ref> The protests led to safety concerns for the teams playing the match and their travelling fans. CONMEBOL consulted both finalists and their football associations, then on 5 November announced the match was moving to the [[Estadio Monumental \"U\"|Estadio Monumental]] in [[Lima]], Peru, due to the ongoing unrest in Chile.<ref>{{citeweb|url= https://www.espn.com/soccer/conmebol-copa-libertadores/story/3982558/copa-libertadores-final-moved-from-santiago-to-lima-due-to-unrest-in-chile|title =Copa Libertadores final moved from Santiago to Lima due to unrest in Chile|date=5 November 2019|work=ESPN|accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThis was the first final to be played as a single match at a neutral venue chosen in advance, replacing the home-and-away format used from 1988 to 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elgrafico.com.ar/articulo/1047/15690/cuando-a-newells-se-le-escapo-su-primera-final-de-copa-libertadores|title=Cuando a Newell's se le escap\u00f3 su primera final de Copa Libertadores|website=El Gr\u00e1fico|language=es|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref> The [[2018 Copa Libertadores Finals|second leg of the 2018 final]] was played at [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]] in [[Madrid]], Spain, the first final held outside of the Americas, after security concerns cancelled the original second leg at the stadium of River Plate in Buenos Aires.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.conmebol.com/es/final-de-la-conmebol-libertadores-2018-se-jugara-el-domingo-9-de-diciembre-en-el-santiago-bernabeu|title=Final de la CONMEBOL Libertadores 2018 se jugar\u00e1 el domingo 9 de diciembre en el Santiago Bernab\u00e9u de Madrid {{!}} CONMEBOL|website=www.conmebol.com|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>\n\n==Show==\nBefore the match, the Argentineans [[Fito P\u00e1ez]] and [[Tini Stoessel]], the Colombian [[Sebasti\u00e1n Yatra]] and the Brazilian [[Anitta (singer)|Anitta]], who performed \"Y dale alegr\u00eda a mi coraz\u00f3n\", by P\u00e1ez. Then two bands identified with the finalist teams participated: [[:es:Turf (banda)|Turf]], for River Plate, and [[Gabriel o Pensador]], for Flamengo. <ref> [http://www.conmebol.com/ en / show-of-international-stars-to-start-the-only-end-of-the-conmebol-liberators-2019 International star show to begin the Single Final of the CONMEBOL Libertadores 2019] </ref>\n\n==Road to the final==\n{{details|2019 Copa Libertadores}}\n''Note: In all scores below, the score of the home team is given first.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=3|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo|Flamengo]]\n!Round\n!colspan=3|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]]\n|-bgcolor=#c1e0ff\n|width=25%|Opponent\n|width=10%|Venue\n|width=10%|Score\n|width=10%|\n|width=25%|Opponent\n|width=10%|Venue\n|width=10%|Score\n|-\n|colspan=3|Bye\n|bgcolor=#c1e0ff|[[2019 Copa Libertadores qualifying stages|Qualifying stages]]\n|colspan=3|Bye\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage#Group D|Group D]]'''\n|rowspan=8 bgcolor=#c1e0ff|[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage|Group stage]]\n|colspan=3|'''[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage#Group A|Group A]]'''\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|BOL|football}} [[Club San Jos\u00e9|San Jos\u00e9]]\n|Away||[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage#D4 v D2|0\u20131]]\n|align=left|{{flagicon|PER|football}} [[Alianza Lima]]\n|Away||[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage#A3 v A1|1\u20131]]\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|ECU}} [[L.D.U. Quito|LDU Quito]]\n|Home||[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage#D2 v D3|3\u20131]]\n|align=left|{{flagicon|CHI}} [[Club Deportivo Palestino|Palestino]]\n|Home||[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage#A1 v A4|0\u20130]]\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|URU}} [[Pe\u00f1arol]]\n|Home||[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage#D2 v D1|0\u20131]]\n|align=left|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Sport Club Internacional|Internacional]]\n|Away||[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage#A2 v A1|2\u20132]]\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|BOL|football}} [[Club San Jos\u00e9|San Jos\u00e9]]\n|Home||[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage#D2 v D4|6\u20131]]\n|align=left|{{flagicon|PER|football}} [[Alianza Lima]]\n|Home||[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage#A1 v A3|3\u20130]]\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|ECU}} [[L.D.U. Quito|LDU Quito]]\n|Away||[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage#D3 v D2|2\u20131]]\n|align=left|{{flagicon|CHI}} [[Club Deportivo Palestino|Palestino]]\n|Away||[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage#A1 v A4|0\u20132]]\n|-\n|align=left|{{flagicon|URU}} [[Pe\u00f1arol]]\n|Away||[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage#D1 v D2|0\u20130]]\n|align=left|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Sport Club Internacional|Internacional]]\n|Home||[[2019 Copa Libertadores group stage#A1 v A2|2\u20132]]\n|-\n|colspan=3 align=center valign=top|\n{{2019 Copa Libertadores group tables|Group D|only_pld_pts=yes|show_matches=no|showteam=FLA}}\n|colspan=3 align=center valign=top|\n{{2019 Copa Libertadores group tables|Group A|only_pld_pts=yes|show_matches=no|showteam=RIV}}\n|-\n|colspan=3|'''[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Seeding|Seed 7]]'''\n|bgcolor=#c1e0ff|[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages|Final stages]]\n|colspan=3|'''[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Seeding|Seed 10]]'''\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=left|{{flagicon|ECU}} [[C.S. Emelec|Emelec]]<br />''(tied 2\u20132 on aggregate, won 4\u20132 on penalties)''\n|Away||[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Match C.1|0\u20132]]\n|rowspan=2 bgcolor=#c1e0ff|[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Round of 16|Round of 16]]\n|rowspan=2 align=left|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Cruzeiro Esporte Clube|Cruzeiro]]<br />''(tied 0\u20130 on aggregate, won 4\u20132 on penalties)''\n|Home||[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Match A.1|0\u20130]]\n|-\n|Home||[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Match C.2|2\u20130]]\n|Away||[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Match A.2|0\u20130]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=left|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Sport Club Internacional|Internacional]]<br />''(won 3\u20131 on aggregate)''\n|Home||[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Match S3.1|2\u20130]]\n|rowspan=2 bgcolor=#c1e0ff|[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Quarterfinals|Quarterfinals]]\n|rowspan=2 align=left|{{flagicon|PAR}} [[Cerro Porte\u00f1o]]<br />''(won 3\u20131 on aggregate)''\n|Home||[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Match S1.1|2\u20130]]\n|-\n|Away||[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Match S3.2|1\u20131]]\n|Away||[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Match S1.1|1\u20131]]\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=left|{{flagicon|BRA}} [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]]<br />''(won 6\u20131 on aggregate)''\n|Away||[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Match F2.1|1\u20131]]\n|rowspan=2 bgcolor=#c1e0ff|[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Semifinals|Semifinals]]\n|rowspan=2 align=left|{{flagicon|ARG}} [[Boca Juniors]]<br />''(won 2\u20131 on aggregate)''\n|Home||[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Match F1.1|2\u20130]]\n|-\n|Home||[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Match F2.2|5\u20130]]\n|Away||[[2019 Copa Libertadores final stages#Match F1.2|0\u20131]]\n|}\n\n==Format==\nThe final is played as a single match at a pre-selected venue, with the higher-seeded team designated as the \"home\" team for administrative purposes.{{Sfn|Reglamento||p=[http://www.conmebol.com/sites/default/files/reglamento-conmebol-libertadores-2019-esp.pdf#page=28 30]}} If scores are level after full time, 30 minutes of extra time would be played. If still tied after extra time, a penalty shoot-out would be used to determine the winner.{{Sfn|Reglamento||p=[http://www.conmebol.com/sites/default/files/reglamento-conmebol-libertadores-2019-esp.pdf#page=29 31]}}<ref>{{cite web |last1=Blitz |first1=Sam |title=Copa Libertadores Final 2019: how to watch, who is playing and how it works |url=https://www.fourfourtwo.com/features/copa-libertadores-final-2019-river-plate-flamengo-how-watch-online-who-playing-rules-extra-time |website=FourFourTwo.com |accessdate=25 November 2019 |date=22 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Match==\n===Summary===\nRiver Plate opened the match in a 2\u20133\u20133\u20132 formation, which allowed their midfield to dominate. This tactic gained them an early lead, when [[Rafael Santos Borr\u00e9]] scored in the 14th minute from a cross by [[Ignacio Fern\u00e1ndez (footballer)|Ignacio Fern\u00e1ndez]].  River Plate had numerous chances for a second goal in the first half: Borr\u00e9 missed a opportunity by inches, [[Nicol\u00e1s De La Cruz]] missed a good chance in the 21st minute, and [[Exequiel Palacios]] had two long-distance shots that nearly went in. However River Plate were unable to capitalise on these opportunities, so at half time the score remained 1-0.<ref name=\"CONMEBOL\">{{cite web |last1=Ellerby |first1=Nick |title=Flamengo stage incredible comeback to beat River Plate and become champions of South America |url=https://www.copalibertadores.com/en/news/flamengo-stage-incredible-comeback-to-beat-river-plate-and/1g0wysu0l7xch1apqbmrl0no1k |website=copalibertadores.com |publisher=CONMEBOL |accessdate=24 November 2019 |date=23 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC1\">{{cite web |last1=Chowdhury |first1=Saj |title=Copa Libertadores: Flamengo beat River Plate with two late goals |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/50532892 |website=BBC |publisher=BBC |accessdate=24 November 2019 |date=23 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nRiver Plate continued to dominate in the early part of the second half. However, Flamengo began to assert themselves on the counter-attack, with [[Gabriel Barbosa]] and [[\u00c9verton Ribeiro]] nearly scoring while Borr\u00e9 was down with an injury. Flamengo substitute [[Diego (footballer, born 1985)|Diego]] was brought on for [[Gerson (footballer, born 1997)|Gerson]] in the 66th minute, and he helped Flamengo turn the match around. Diego began several counter-attacks, including in the 75th minute when he linked up with [[Bruno Henrique Pinto]] and Gabriel. The score was still 1-0 in the 89th minute, with River Plate seeking to finish off the game, when Flamengo's Arrascaeta won the ball from [[Lucas Pratto]] in his own half, and started a counter-attack by passing to Bruno Henrique. Henrique dribbled the ball down the left wing and cut inside; near the opposing goal, he passed the ball to Arrascaeta, who avoided the goalkeeper's challenge to pass to an open Gabriel who scored a tap-in to tie the game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2019/nov/23/flamengo-v-river-plate-copa-libertadores-final-live|title=Flamengo 2\u20131 River Plate: Copa Libertadores final \u2013 as it happened|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|first=Will|last=Unwin|date=23 November 2019|accessdate=24 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThree minutes later (in the second minute of [[injury time]]), Diego launched a deep pass from his own half that both River Plate [[centre back]]s missed. This allowed Gabriel to score again, giving Flamengo a 2-1 lead. The sudden reversal of fortune caused tempers to flare: Palacios kicked Bruno Henrique in the 95th minute, for which he received a [[Penalty card#Red card|red card]]. Gabriel Barbosa sarcastically applauded the referee in response; he also received a red card. The match ended shortly thereafter. After being behind for most of the match, Flamengo emerged as last minute champions, winning their second Copa Libertadores title.<ref name=\"CONMEBOL\" /><ref name=\"BBC1\" />\n\n===Details===\n<onlyinclude>{{Football box\n|date       = {{Start date|2019|11|23|df=y}}\n|time       = {{UTZ|15:00|-5}}\n|team1      = [[Clube de Regatas do Flamengo|Flamengo]] {{flagicon|BRA}}\n|score      = 2\u20131\n|team2      = {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Club Atl\u00e9tico River Plate|River Plate]]\n|goals1     = [[Gabriel Barbosa]] {{goal|89||90+2}}\n|goals2     = [[Rafael Santos Borr\u00e9|Borr\u00e9]] {{goal|14}}\n|stadium    = [[Estadio Monumental \"U\"|Estadio Monumental]], [[Lima]]\n|attendance =\n|referee    = [[Roberto Tobar]] ([[Football Federation of Chile|Chile]])\n|report     = http://estadisticas.conmebol.com/html/v3/index.html?channel=deportes.futbol.libertadores.460771&lang=es_LA\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n{| width=92%\n|-\n|{{Football kit\n |pattern_la = _flamengo1920h\n |pattern_b  = _flamengo1920h\n |pattern_ra = _flamengo1920h\n |pattern_sh = _adidasred\n |pattern_so = _hoops_re