3.ods\n|publisher  =HM Government. Office for National Statistics\n|title      =Tables for 'Police workforce, England and Wales, 31 March 2013\n|accessdate =29 May 2014\n|date       =31 March 2013}}</ref>\n|unsworntype     = Police Community Support Officer\n|unsworn         = 318<ref name=\"HO page\"/>\n|multinational   =\n|electeetype     = [[Police and Crime Commissioner]]\n|minister1name   = [[Keith Hunter (police commissioner)|Keith Hunter]], [[Labour Party (UK)|(L)]]\n|chief1name      = Lee Freeman\n|chief1position  = [[Chief Constable]]\n|chief2name      = Chris Rowley\n|chief2position  = [[Deputy Chief Constable]]\n|chief3name      = Scott Young\n|chief3position  = [[Assistant Chief Constable]] (Local Policing)\n|chief4name      = Chris Noble\n|chief4position  = [[Assistant Chief Constable]] (Crime)\n|chief5name      = Nannie Shackleton \n|chief5position  = [[Assistant Chief Constable]] (Resources)\n|parentagency    =\n|child1agency    =\n|unittype        = [[Basic Command Unit|Division]]\n|unitname        = \n|officetype      = \n|officename      = \n|provideragency  =\n|uniformedas     =\n|stationtype     =\n|stations        =\n|airbases        = \n|lockuptype      = Stations\n|lockups         = 19\n|vehicle1type    =\n|vehicles1       =\n|boat1type       =\n|boats1          =\n|animal1type     =\n|animals1        =\n|person1name     =\n|person1reason   =\n|person1type     =\n|programme1      =\n|activity1name   =\n|activitytype    =\n|anniversary1    =\n|award1          =\n|website         = [http://www.humberside.police.uk/ www.humberside.police.uk]\n|footnotes       =\n|reference       =\n}}\n'''Humberside Police''' is the [[territorial police force]] responsible for policing Hull, Goole, Grimsby and Scunthorpe. \n\nThe current [[Chief Constable]] is [[Lee Freeman (police officer)|Lee Freeman]]. Following the sudden departure of Justine Curran, Lee Freeman took over as the Deputy Chief Constable in February 2017. He was appointed as Chief Constable In June 2017.<ref name=\"Freeman\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/news/hull-east-yorkshire-news/lee-freeman-named-new-humberside-136632|title=Lee Freeman named as new Humberside Police chief constable|last=Robinson|first=Hannah|date=26 June 2017|work=Hull Daily Mail|accessdate=26 June 2017}}</ref> \n\nLee Freeman was previously the Assistant Chief Constable of Lincolnshire Police, from 2013 - 2015. Freeman transferred to Humberside Police in May 2015.\n\nHumberside Police's [[Home Office radio|Home Office Radio]] Code is XH 16. \n\n==History==\n\nHumberside Police was created in 1974 following a merger of previous forces under the [[Local Government Act 1972]], along with the [[Metropolitan and non-metropolitan counties of England|non-metropolitan county]] of [[Humberside]]. \n\nProposals made by the [[Home Secretary]] on 21 March 2006 would have seen the force merge with [[North Yorkshire Police]], [[South Yorkshire Police]] and [[West Yorkshire Police]] to form a strategic police force for the entire region.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/west_yorkshire/4829466.stm\n|title=Police merger plan is recommended\n|accessdate=15 November 2007\n|date=21 March 2006\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|work=[[BBC News Online]]\n}}\n</ref> These proposals have since been 'put on hold' by the government.\n\n===Humberside Police Authority===\nFollowing the abolition of Humberside in 1996, the local council members of the [[Police Authority]] were appointed by a joint committee of the councils of the East Riding of Yorkshire, [[Hull City Council|Kingston upon Hull]], North Lincolnshire, and North East Lincolnshire. On 21 November 2012 the Police Authority was made redundant by the introduction of the [[Police and Crime Commissioner]].\n\nThe Humberside [[Police Authority]], at the time it ceased to exist, had 17 members in total; nine Local Authority Elected members from the area's four unitary authorities and eight independent members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humberside-pa.org.uk/about-us/hpa-members/|title=Humberside Police Authority (http://www.humberside-pa.org.uk)|date=12 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729074338/http://www.humberside-pa.org.uk/about-us/hpa-members/|archivedate=29 July 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Chief Constables==\n* 1974 \u2013 1976   : Robert Walton\n* 1976 \u2013 1991   : David Hall<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/news/grimsby-news/tributes-longest-serving-chief-constable-1637680|title=tributes to Longeest Serving Police Officer|publisher= Grimsby Argus|accessdate= 22 June 2018}}</ref>\n* 1991 \u2013 1999   : D. Anthony Leonard\n* 1999 \u2013 2005  : [[David Westwood]]\n* 2005 \u2013 2013  : [[Tim Hollis|Timothy Stancliffe Hollis]]\n* 2013 \u2013 2017   : [[Justine Curran]]\n* 2017 \u2013           : [[Lee Freeman (police officer)|Lee Freeman]]\n\n===Resignation of Justine Curran===\nFrom March 2013 to February 2017 the [[Chief Constable]] of Humberside Police was Justine Curran, previously Chief Constable of [[Tayside Police]] in Scotland before the introduction of the national [[Police Scotland]] service on 1 April 2013. Her appointment was unanimously approved by the Humberside Police and Crime panel after Humberside Police and Crime Commissioner, [[Matthew Grove]], proposed her for the post.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-21352394|title=Humberside Police appoints its first female chief constable|date=6 February 2013|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=6 February 2013}}</ref> Curran took over the position from [[Tim Hollis]] [[CBE]] [[Queen's Police Medal|QPM]] who retired from the service in March 2013.\n\nOn 11 November 2015, it was revealed that Curran had claimed for more than \u00a339,000 in expenses for her relocation from Tayside to Humberside in March 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Named-shamed-Humberside-Police-chief-Justine/story-28154326-detail/story.html|title=Named and shamed: Humberside Police chief Justine Curran claimed \u00a339,000 in expenses to move to area|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120135725/http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/Named-shamed-Humberside-Police-chief-Justine/story-28154326-detail/story.html|archivedate=20 November 2015|url-status=dead|work=Grimsby Telegraph|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter [[Keith Hunter (police commissioner)|Keith Hunter]] was elected as [[Police and crime commissioner|Police and Crime Commissioner]] in May 2016, Curran was given six months to improve the force after it was rated inadequate by [[Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Constabulary]] (HMIC). Nine months later, after a further HMIC inspection which identified further \"significant failings\", Hunter asked Curran to consider her position, and she announced her retirement.<ref name=\":0\" /> She left on 20 February 2017, 18 months before she had been due to retire.<ref name=\"Humberside Police Chief Constable Justine Curran steps down\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-39031306|title=Humberside Police Chief Constable Justine Curran steps down|date=20 February 2017|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=21 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, it was revealed that Hunter had \"lost confidence\" in Curran and was \"completely undermined\" by her when it was decided to withhold the findings of an HMIC investigation which revealed further inadequacies within the force. Hunter sought legal advice, and Curran was allowed to retire before the statutory procedure to remove a [[Chief constable|Chief Constable]] was started.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/news/hull-east-yorkshire-news/ex-police-chief-says-didnt-381097|title=What ex-police chief said in revealing first interview since sudden exit|last=Leeson|first=Lucy|date=25 August 2017|work=Hull Daily Mail|accessdate=25 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nLee Freeman, a former Assistant Chief Constable in Lincolnshire from August 2013 who had joined Humberside in May 2015, took over as Deputy Chief Constable on Curran's departure. He was appointed temporary Chief Constable in May 2017 and the position was made permanent on 26 June 2017.<ref name=\"Freeman\"/>\n\n==Police fleet==\n{{anchor|Police cars}}{{anchor|Police video}}\n\nHumberside uses a wide variety of vehicles, including both marked and unmarked police vehicles. \u00a0\n\nAll marked police vehicles utilize Battenberg livery, as opposed to the traditional livery previously used by Humberside Police. Further to this all marked police vehicles use LED lightbars. The older halogen light bars have been phased out.\n\nThe LED light-bars are much easier to see, due to the increased lumen output. The LED light bars contain red lights at the rear, which can be used to indicate to other road users that the vehicle is stationary. They also contain both left and right spots lights, called side alley lights, that can be used to illuminate door numbers when quickly trying to find an address.\n\nThe roads policing unit utilize a premier hazard light-bar. This offers a more customizable light bar, with the option to cycle between flash patterns. It also allows officers the choice, of illuminating only the front or rear LED\u2019s.\n\nAdditionally, the road policing unit vehicles contain a premier hazard message board. This can display a scrolling message to drivers, such as \u201cFollow Me\u201d\n\nIRT (Incident response team) vehicles benefit from a single video camera with no audio function. This is located at the front of the vehicle, near the rear-view mirror. The camera remains recording for 20 minutes after the vehicle\u2019s ignition has been turned off. IRT vehicles also contain a black box, that records a vehicles speed, acceleration, braking time, and light usage. This is automatically uploaded to a \u2018cloud\u2019 storage device via WIFI, once the vehicle returns to station.\n\nRoads Policing vehicles contain a Pro-vida recording camera. This is able to record audio, as well as display the speed of the vehicle, and its location.\n\nAdditionally, Roads Policing Vehicles contain ANPR capabilities. This automatically reads the registration plate of a vehicle, and displays information with regards to insurance details, including the holders name and d.o.b. as well as the tax and mot status of a vehicle. It further provides information to any \u2018markers\u2019 placed on a vehicle or its named driver. Humberside Police traffic officers also carry a handheld Pro Lazer 4 speed gun, drugs swipe and a Breathalyzer. IRT patrol cars do not contain a ANPR device and manually have to search a vehicles detail using their radio or handheld computer.\n\n<!--Does this need to be in here..?\n==== <u>Emergency Driving Course</u> ====\nIRT officers are placed on a 3 weeks blue light driving course. This is known as basic emergency driving. If Police officers are not trained in emergency blue light driving, they may not utilize their emergency lights and sirens, unless the vehicle is stationary. In this scenario, blue lights may be used as means of warning such as required when directing traffic.\n\nAlthough except by Section 87 of the Road Traffic Act, meaning officers cannot technically be done for speeding whilst travelling on blue lights, internal policy states an officer must only drive a maximum of 20mph over the speed limit. IRT officers cannot pursue a vehicle unless they are initial phase pursuit trained. This does not apply to traffic officers.\n\nThe use of Blue Lights is not mandatory, when an officer is appropriately trained, and responding to an emergency. The Blue lights are for the benefit of public road users to act as a warning of the vehicles speed. Officers may choose to, if they wish to drive in an emergency, without using emergency lighting equipment. An example of this may include making a \u2018silent approach\u2019 to a victim of crime, where an offender is still on scene, and subsequently the Police officer does not wish to advertise their presence.\n\nUpon qualifying as a Traffic or Firearms Police Officer, applicants are placed on an further 3.5 weeks advanced emergency driving course. Subsequently, Traffic Police Officers are no longer restricted by internal policy, as to how fast they may travel. Instead they must continually risk asses their speed, to ensure it is appropriate.\n\nTraffic Police Officers are also taught how to make tactical contact and are trained in T-Pack manoeuvres.\n\n== Vehicles in use: ==\n'''<u>IRT (Incident Response Team) Vehicles</u>'''\n\nThese are vehicles used by the IRT for the purpose of general policing. These vehicles include Peugeot 308, a Vauxhall Astra and Ford Transit Boxer vans. The Ford Transit Boxer Van contain a cell in the rear capable of housing 2 prisoners. In 2019 Humberside Police trialled a Peugeot 308, that contains a cell, capable of housing 1 prisoner. \u00a0\n\nIRT officers also use a Mercedes Sprinter van. This is primarily used for carrying a large number of officers, such as required when providing PSU officers for public order.\n\nIRT also utilize the Mercedes Sprinter for patrolling the areas surrounding pubs and clubs at night. The Mercedes Sprinters, like the Ford Transit, also contain a cell in the rear capable of housing 2 prisoners.\n\nHumberside Police had previously won the top award in the National Energy Efficiency Awards by running the vast majority of its fleet on Liquified Petroleum Gas. Most Protons where converted to run on LPG. This was reverted, and the vehicles where converted back to running on unleaded petrol, due both reliability issues and the rising cost of LPG. Humberside Police have practically phased out the aging [[Proton Waja|Proton Impian]]. Most patrol vehicles now run on diesel.\n\n'''<u>Communities Policing</u>'''\n\nThe community\u2019s team within Humberside Police use a Vauxhall Corsa as their main vehicle. This comes in two different liveries. One being a fully marked police vehicle, and the other being a marked Police Community Support Officer vehicle.\n\nThe communities policing team may also use an unmarked Peugeot 208, as well as the above-mentioned vehicle from IRT.\n\n'''<u>Detectives & Investigating officers</u>'''\n\nBoth detectives and investigating officers use unmarked Peugeot 208\u2019s to carry out enquires. These vehicles do not contain lights and sirens and are not to be utilized for front line policing.\n\n'''<u>Crime Scene Investigators</u>'''\n\nHumberside Police scenes of crime, police staff use a Vauxhall Vivaro vans as there means of transport. These vehicles are marked with police Battenberg; however they do not house LED emergency lighting. This is due to the role of a CSI officer being a civilian one.\n\n'''<u>Roads Policing Unit</u>'''\n\nHumberside Police utilize both a BMW X5\u2019s and a BMW 330D for the purpose of roads policing.\n\nThe BMW 5 series primarily belong to Humberside Polices Firearms unit, however, are utilized when necessary by traffic officers such as when poor road conditions dictate.\n\nBoth the BMW X5\u2019s and BMW 330D\u2019s come in marked and unmarked variants.\n\nThe Roads Policing Unit and Humberside Polices Firearms Unit are now based at Melton, on the North Bank of the Humber as opposed to being based in various locations around the force. This has enabled the section to respond to incidents more quickly and efficiently.\n\nHumberside Police\u2019s roads policing unit did previously use the BMW F11, 5 series 530D. However, only a few remain in use, as they where deemed too expensive.\n\nContrary to popular belief the Roads Policing Vehicles are not specially tuned. They do not benefit from a remapped engine for greater power output. The primary focus of a police pursuit is safety. This is the reason Humberside Police opt for the BMW 330d as opposed to the BMW 335d.\n\nAgain, contrary to popular belief, Humberside Police do not use Volvo\u2019s as Traffic Police cars anymore. In 2019 Humberside Police did trial the Volvo V90, however the trail showed the Volvo V90 performed poorly for pursuits in Urban areas, in comparison to the well-established BMW 330d therefore was never ordered.\n\nIn 2008, Humberside Police made a statement, to deter offending criminals from utilizing the road network. Humberside Police purchased a 5 high powered vehicles. The vehicles often patrolled in the following trio;\n\nThe first of the trio was a Lexus IS F. Under the bonnet it contained a 5.0 Litre V8, producing 417 bhp. The Lexus IS F had a 0-60 of 4.6 seconds. The registration plate of this vehicle was YX58 FLE.\n\nThe second of the trio was a Mitsubishi Lancer EVO X FQ-360. This produced 354 bhp with a 0-60 of 4.1 seconds. The registration plates of this vehicle was YX58 FLA, and YX58 FLC.\n\nThe final vehicle in the trio was a BMW 335d Estate, producing 281 BHP with a 0-60 of 5.9 seconds. The registration plates of this vehicle was YX58 FLB and YX58 FLD. This BMW offered Humberside Police insight into the pros and cons of using a BMW 335d, as opposed to the standard BMW 330d.\n\nIn 2004 Humberside Police purchased a Subaru Impreza WRX STI, producing 261 BHP. The registration plate of this vehicle was YX54 CXC. This was a continuation of the Subaru Impreza Turbo 2000 AWD, purchased by Humberside Police in 1998. It produced 208 bhp and was notably faster than most vehicles, at the time of purchase. The registration of this vehicle was R191 PKH.\n\nThe Subaru Impreza Turbo 2000 AWD was so iconic and popular amongst citizens, it was made into a scale model toy. Auto-art made a 1:18 scale model version costing around \u00a380. Trofeu and vanguards made a 1:48 scale model costing around \u00a330.\n\n'''<u>Dog Handlers</u>''' \n\nHumberside Police Dog Handlers use both Vauxhall Zafira's and Ford Mondeo Estates. Both vehicles contain a kennel in the rear that is air conditioned. The kennel can hold two dogs, so officers can take out both there general policing Belgium Shepard dog and the and their drugs and money detection Spaniel.\n\n'''<u>Driver training Unit</u>'''\n\nThe Humberside Police Driver training unit, responsible for training officers how to drive on blue lights in emergency conditions, utilize several unmarked Skoda VRs.\n\nThe Skoda VRs vehicles are used only for this purpose and are not utilized by traffic officers.\n\nThe driver training unit also utilizes one unmarked Vauxhall Astra.\n\nNotably until 2018, Humberside\u2019s drive training unit did also use a 2004 BMW 530d. \n<br />\n\n<u>Specialist vehicles</u>\n\nHumberside Police no longer operate there own Police Helicopter. On Thursday 27th of September 2016, the Force Helicopter was withdrawn from service. Aerial support is now provided by the [[National Police Air Service]] (NPAS) from their Carr Gate base, in Wakefield.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/humberside-police-to-axe-helicopter-and-join-national-air-support-service-by-end-of-this-month/story-29700229-detail/story.html|title=Humberside Police to axe helicopter and join national air support service by end of this month|last=|first=|date=9 September 2016|accessdate=21 January 2017|newspaper=Grimsby Telegraph}}{{dead link|date=December 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In September 2019, Humberside Police struck a deal with Humberside Fire & Rescue, and now share both the DJI Matrice 210 and the DJI Mavic 2 Enterprise drones. Both the Police & Fire service contribute towards the operating costs. \n\n\nIn 2019 Humberside Police replaced there aging Mercedes Sprinter Prison Bus, with an Iveco Prison Bus. The Prison Bus is capable of holding 8 prisoners at a time, and is utilized as a holding area for detainee's at large events, where there high likelihood numerous people will be arrested. It is also used for transporting a number of prisoners from one location to another. \n-->\n==Performance ==\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| direction = vertical\n| width1 = 250\n| width2 = 250\n| image1 = Lexus IS-F Humberside Police.jpg\n| image2 = '06 Proton Impian 1.6 GLS Humberside Police (U.K.) car.jpg\n| footer = Humberside Police [[Lexus IS-F]]. (above)<br> A [[Proton Impian]] of the Humberside Police. (below)\n}}\n\nThe force underperformed for a number of years. In October 2006 it was named as the worst-performing police force in the country (jointly with [[Northamptonshire Police]]), based on data released from the [[Home Office]]<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/6079944.stm\n|title=Humberside 'worst police force'\n|accessdate=15 November 2007\n|date=24 October 2006\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|work=[[BBC News Online]]\n}}\n</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/pdfs/24_10_06_police.pdf|accessdate=8 April 2013|title=Police Performance Assessments 2005/06|publisher=Home Office}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 the force moved off the bottom of the unofficial league table thanks to \"major improvements\" in performance, according to the Home Office.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/humber/7035407.stm\n|title=Police force sheds 'worst' label\n|accessdate=10 October 2007\n|date=9 October 2007\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|work=[[BBC News Online]]}}</ref>\n\nPerformance continued to improve, with a 20% reduction in total recorded crime as at March 2009. Recorded vehicle crime was down 39%, domestic burglary was down 12%, and robbery was down 36%. Home Office figures published in July 2009 showed that from 2007/08 to 2008/09, Humberside Police had the second highest increase of all forces in England and Wales in the percentage of [[British Crime Survey]] respondents who said that their local police do an excellent or good job.\n\nAfter inspections by [[Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Constabulary]] (HMIC) between April and August 2009, their report identified Humberside Police as one of the top eight forces in the country.\n\nIn April 2009 the force was cited as the poorest performing force for completing Criminal Record Bureau (CRB) checks. The Home Office requirement is for 95% of requests to be completed within 14 days; Humberside Police completed just 15%. As such checks are often a condition of employment, this failure caused delays for those waiting to start work.<ref>{{cite news|title=Police admit crime check delays|last=|first=|work=Grimsby Telegraph|date=29 April 2009|id = {{ProQuest|426042515}}}}</ref>\n\n[[Graham Stuart (UK politician)|Graham Stuart]], MP for [[Beverley and Holderness]], said he was disgusted with this failure. He said, \"The delay in processing them stops people taking up work and has a crippling impact on voluntary groups who have to get their volunteers approved. The Humberside Police are seriously lagging behind virtually every other constabulary in the country and local people are being let down.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grahamstuart.com/index.php?sectionid=3&pagenumber=223|title=Graham Stuart 'disgusted' with CRB checking performance by police|last=|first=|date=6 May 2009|website=|publisher=Graham Stuart MP|accessdate=14 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, it was revealed that officer morale in the force was the lowest in the country, with 84.5% of officers saying that their morale was currently low, compared to 70.2% nationally.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Officer-morale-Humberside-Police-lowest-country/story-27948159-detail/story.html|title=Officer morale at Humberside Police lowest in the country \u2013 survey|work=Hull Daily Mail|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151012000123/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Officer-morale-Humberside-Police-lowest-country/story-27948159-detail/story.html|archivedate=12 October 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=17 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 October 2015, in a report published by HMIC, Humberside Police was the only force in the country classed as inadequate. The report suggested that the force had a \"limited understanding\" of demand for its services, and raised \"serious concerns\" over the way it was organised. HM Inspector of Constabulary Mike Cunningham said: \"Humberside Police has a limited understanding of the current and future demand for its services and, as it is unable to fully match resources to demand in some important areas, this affects its ability to provide a good service to the public.\" Chief Constable [[Justine Curran]] said the force had \"moved on\" since then.<ref>{{cite news|title = Humberside Police rated 'inadequate' by inspectors|url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-34573513|work= BBC News|accessdate = 20 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nSimilarly, the Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC) released its annual statistics of police complaints from forces throughout the country: Humberside Police performed better than average in many areas; e.g. the number of complaints ahd decreased by 4% compared to an increase of 6% nationally. But the number of appeals by dissatisfied complainants had increased by 24%: three times the national average.<ref>{{cite news|title = Police report reveals complaint statistics|url = http://www.beverleyguardian.co.uk/news/local/police-report-reveals-complaint-statistics-1-7514564|work= Beverley Guardian|accessdate = 22 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, it was revealed that thousands of telephone calls to the [[Single Non-Emergency Number|101 service]] were being abandoned; the problem had reached its peak in June 2015 when over 11,000 calls were abandoned.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Thousands-calls-Humberside-Police-unanswered-new/story-28094740-detail/story.html|title=Thousands of calls to Humberside Police go unanswered new figures reveal|work=Hull Daily Mail|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119223719/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Thousands-calls-Humberside-Police-unanswered-new/story-28094740-detail/story.html|archivedate=19 November 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=2 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 November 2015 the [[East Riding of Yorkshire Council]] agreed to reconvene a panel to review the force after October's HMIC inspection. The panel ended up criticising both police and crime commissioner [[Matthew Grove]] and [[chief constable]] [[Justine Curran]] for refusing to attend one of its meetings. This had led the council to write a critical letter to the parliamentary committee for standards in public life, highlighting concerns over a lack of proper consultation over the reorganisation{{Fix|text=what reorganisation?}}. Speaking at the full council meeting, Cllr. Owen said the panel's concerns had been vindicated by the HMIC report. He said \"all public sector bodies are facing huge financial pressures and I fully appreciate the pressures we all face, and Humberside Police are no different, recovering from a number of years of having to improve performance in a climate of low funding and other pressures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/East-Riding-Council-review-Humberside-Police/story-28201289-detail/story.html|title=East Riding Council to review Humberside Police restructure amid 'grave concerns'|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119215619/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/East-Riding-Council-review-Humberside-Police/story-28201289-detail/story.html|archivedate=19 November 2015|url-status=dead|work=Hull Daily Mail|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, 12 months after Curran's departure, Humberside Police were formally disengaged{{clarify|date=September 2018}} by HMICFRS{{clarify|date=September 2018}} and assessed as sufficiently improved and stable to be removed from what were in effect \"special meaures\"\n\nIn August 2018, in the annual Police Federation Pay and Morale Survey, Humberside were officially recorded as the most improved police force in the country in terms of police officers' reported levels of personal morale. The survey placed the force 3rd out of 43 forces across England and Wales; the previous year the results were reported locally as Humberside having the lowest morale in the country.\n\n== Custody suites ==\n\nHumberside Police has two Custody Suites, that operate 24/7 and hold prisoners which have been arrested by officers in the force. The two Custody Suites are located at;\n\n- Clough Road, Hull\n\n- Birchin Way, Grimsby\n\nThe amount of cells that each Custody Suite has is shown in the table below.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Police Station !! Number of Cells\n|-\n| Hull Clough Road || 40\n|-\n| Grimsby || 36\n|-\n| Scunthorpe || **Closed in 2019**\n|-\n|}\n\nThe 40 cell Custody suite at Clough Road Police Station was built as a state of the art replacement for the Queens Gardens Police Station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/prisons/wp-content/uploads/sites/4/2014/03/humberside-2012.pdf|title=Report on an unannounced inspection visit to police custody suites in Humberside|date=3\u20136 January 2012|website=Criminal Justice Inspectorates|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002757/http://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/prisons/wp-content/uploads/sites/4/2014/03/humberside-2012.pdf|archivedate=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, both the Scunthorpe Custody Suite and the Grimsby, Victoria Road Custody Suite shut. Prisoners are now held in a \u00a314&nbsp;million, 36 cell Custody Suite, located at Birchin Way, Grimsby. The new cells are state of the art, with many facilities including a secure holding bay for arriving prisoners, CCTV monitoring throughout, and special 'orange' holding cell for vulnerable prisoners.{{fact|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Controversy ==\n\nThe 1998 [[death of Christopher Alder]], a black man who was [[unlawful killing|unlawfully killed]] while in the custody of Humberside Police, led to an investigation by the [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]] and a subsequent apology by the government in the [[European Court of Human Rights]], admitting that it had failed to meet its obligations regarding preservation of life and ensuring no person is subjected to \"inhuman or degrading treatment\".<ref name=\"stokes2\">{{Cite news|title=Ex-para in police station was killed unlawfully|last=Stokes|first=Paul|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=25 August 2000|page=11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Government pays out over death of 'wrong body' Falklands veteran Christopher Alder|work=[[The Yorkshire Post]]|location=Leeds|date=22 November 2011}}</ref> Five Humberside Police officers were charged with [[manslaughter]] and [[misconduct in public office]] but the trial collapsed and the judge ordered the jury to find the officers not guilty on all charges.<ref name=\"mintowt\">{{Cite news|title=Death police go free: Judge clears officers who laughed and chatted as ex-Para died in custody|last=Mintowt-Czyz|first=Lech|work=[[Daily Mail]]|location=London|date=22 June 2002|page=32}}</ref>\n\nHumberside Police shot to the national headlines in mid-2004 when it refused to dismiss Chief Constable [[David Westwood]] despite instructions from the then [[Home Secretary]], [[David Blunkett]].<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3860503.stm\n|title=Authority's statement in full\n|accessdate=15 November 2007\n|date=2 July 2004\n|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]\n}}\n</ref> The Home Secretary eventually obtained a court order suspending Westwood.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3860707.stm\n|title=Embattled police chief suspended\n|accessdate=15 November 2007\n|date=2 July 2004\n|publisher=[[BBC]]\n|work=[[BBC News Online]]\n}}\n</ref> The force had come under pressure to dismiss Westwood when the [[Soham Murders|Soham Inquiry]] apportioned part of the blame to Humberside Police for not properly informing the authorities of [[Grimsby]]-born Ian Huntley, who was known to Humberside Police and local [[social services]], after reports of nine [[sexual offences]] of which Huntley had been suspected, and also an alleged burglary. In only one of the sex offence investigations was Huntley charged (with rape) and remanded in custody, but the case was dropped due to insufficient evidence, and his burglary case was [[Lie on file|left on file]]. Huntley was not convicted of any crime (his only actual conviction was for a minor motoring offence in 1993), and Humberside Police did not adequately inform the authorities in [[Cambridgeshire]] about Huntley when he moved to [[Soham]] to work as a school caretaker. He was found guilty of murdering two 10-year-old girls (Holly Wells and Jessica Chapman) in 2003.\n\nThis led to the Bichard enquiry for the police force and the Kelly report for the local council ([[North East Lincolnshire Council]]).<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bichard|first1=Michael|title=The Bichard Enquiry Report|url=http://dera.ioe.ac.uk/6394/1/report.pdf|website=dera.ioe|publisher=UK Government|accessdate=12 February 2018|date=22 June 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kelly|first1=Christopher|title=Serious Case North East Lincolnshire 1995 - 2001|url=http://image.guardian.co.uk/sys-files/Society/documents/2004/07/21/seriouscasereviewreportfinal.pdf|website=guardian.co.uk|publisher=North East Lincolnshire Area Child Protection Committee|accessdate=12 February 2018|date=21 July 2004}}</ref>\n\nIt returned to the headlines in 2005 when [[Colin Inglis (politician)|Colin Inglis]], its chairman at the time of the crisis, appeared in court charged with indecent assaults against children dating back to the 1980s.<ref>\n{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/humber/4077080.stm|title=Police authority chief suspended|accessdate=15 November 2007\n|date=9 June 2005|publisher=[[BBC]]|work=[[BBC News Online]]}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/4436340.stm|title=Ex-police authority head charged|accessdate=15 November 2007|date=14 November 2005|publisher=[[BBC]]|work=[[BBC News Online]]}}\n</ref> Inglis was cleared of all charges in July 2006.<ref>\n{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/humber/5187612.stm|title=Ex-council chief cleared of abuse|accessdate=15 November 2007|date=17 July 2006|publisher=[[BBC]]|work=[[BBC News Online]]}}\n</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, former Detective Chief Superintendent Colin Andrews was convicted of common assault, harassment, stalking, and witness intimidation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Humberside detective Colin Andrews guilty of stalking|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-30957542|accessdate=23 January 2015|agency=BBC News|date=23 January 2015}}</ref> Court testimony revealed that other senior officers in Humberside Police questioned whether an investigation into Andrews' conduct should have gone ahead, concerned by \"the 'dirt' he might throw\" and the damage caused to the force's reputation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Senior-police-officers-asked-inquiry-Colin/story-25757190-detail/story.html|title=Senior police officers asked if inquiry into Colin Andrews 'should go ahead', trial hears|date=24 December 2014|work=Hull Daily Mail|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924045014/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Senior-police-officers-asked-inquiry-Colin/story-25757190-detail/story.html|archivedate=24 September 2015|url-status=dead|last1=Bristow|first1=Simon|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref> One victim, a police inspector, expressed fear of a [[Goole]]-based \"mafia\" of senior officers that included Andrews.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Police-inspector-worried-mafia-Colin-Andrews/story-25703394-detail/story.html|title=Police inspector was worried about 'mafia', Colin Andrews trial hears|date=13 December 2014|work=Hull Daily Mail|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222090510/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Police-inspector-worried-mafia-Colin-Andrews/story-25703394-detail/story.html|archivedate=22 December 2015|url-status=dead|last1=Bristow|first1=Simon|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, a sergeant with 27 years service was dismissed after kicking a 16-year-old boy in the head following a chase. Sergeant John Stevenson was involved in one of the most high-profile cases in Humberside Police's recent history when he arrested his own boss, Colin Andrews, who was found guilty of stalking, harassment and assault in January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Humberside-Police-Sergeant-John-Mick-Stevenson/story-28207232-detail/story.html#comments|title=Humberside Police Sergeant John 'Mick' Stevenson sacked for kicking teenager in head|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151225200648/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Humberside-Police-Sergeant-John-Mick-Stevenson/story-28207232-detail/story.html|archivedate=25 December 2015|url-status=dead|work=Hull Daily Mail|accessdate=19 November 2015}}</ref> Many speculated that the sergeant was used as a scapegoat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Sacked-Humberside-Police-sergeant-John-Mick/story-28214201-detail/story.html|title=Sacked Humberside Police sergeant John 'Mick' Stevenson 'hung, drawn and quartered'|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151123231812/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Sacked-Humberside-Police-sergeant-John-Mick/story-28214201-detail/story.html|archivedate=23 November 2015|url-status=dead|work=Hull Daily Mail|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nA man who has no connection with Humberside, was questioned over the telephone by Humberside Police for 34 minutes because he liked a Twitter posting that questioned transgender ideology.<ref>{{cite web\n | url =https://www.grimsbytelegraph.co.uk/news/grimsby-news/humberside-police-transgender-twitter-thinking-2466084?_ga=2.242272002.1829293347.1578862903-721712930.1578862903\n | title =Humberside Police quiz man after he likes 'offensive transgender limerick'\n | last =Keane\n | first =Duncan\n | date =25 January 2019\n | website =Grimsby Telegraph\n | access-date =12 January 2020 }}</ref>  Characterising this as an act characteristic of an Orwellian society, the High Court ruled in 2020 that this questionning was unlawful and represented a disproportionate interference with the man's right to freedom of expression<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-lincolnshire-51501202</ref>\n\n==Police and Crime Commissioner (PCC)==\n{{See also|England and Wales police and crime commissioner elections, 2012|England and Wales police and crime commissioner elections, 2016}}\nOn Thursday 15 November 2012 the people of Humberside went to the [[polling station]]s to vote for a candidate for the [[Humberside Police and Crime Commissioner]] for the Humberside Police, as did the rest of the people of England and Wales, except the [[Metropolitan Police]] area, to vote for a PCC in their respective police services. Following the poll [[Matthew Grove]] was elected as the new [[Police and Crime Commissioner]] for the Humberside Police area.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-20346472|title=Prescott beaten by Conservatives in Humberside PCC vote|date=16 November 2012|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=18 November 2012}}</ref> When the commissioner took up office the existing [[Police Authority]] was abolished.\n\nOn 6 May 2016, Labour's [[Keith Hunter (police commissioner)|Keith Hunter]] was elected as Humberside Police's next PCC, receiving over 76,128 votes in total during the second round, compared to Grove's 51,757.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/election-2016-35993241|title=Labour's Keith Hunter elected PCC for Humberside|website=BBC News|accessdate=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Documentaries==\n\n===''Traffic Cops''===\nHumberside Police have taken part in the [[BBC One]] documentary series of ''[[Traffic Cops]]'', the programme shows the day-to-day aspects of a Police Officer within the Traffic Department of the Service and the incidents and emergencies that they deal with which often, but not always, relate to roads policing issues.\n\nThe Humberside Police Traffic Department has also taken part in the separate spin-off series billed as ''Traffic Cops Specials'', entitled ''Motorway Cops'' on occasions, which often shows the [[Central Motorway Police Group]], however often includes ''Humberside'' and numerous other forces Motorway Cops as they each deal with Incidents and Emergencies that occur on the motorways.\n\n===''The Lock Up''===\nHumberside Police recently participated in a documentary serious named ''[[The Lock Up (television series)|The Lock Up]]'', where cameras followed Police and Custody officers in their work at the Custody Suite at Humberside Police Headquarters on Priory Road, [[Cottingham, East Riding of Yorkshire]].\n\nThe documentary has had 2 series, the first aired on [[BBC Three]] which started showing on 4 February 2011<ref name=\"young drunks\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thisishullandeastriding.co.uk/news/Hull-s-young-drunks-TV-tonight-BBC-screens-Lock/article-3184546-detail/article.html|title=Hull's young drunks on TV tonight as BBC screens The Lock Up|date=4 February 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110214095522/http://www.thisishullandeastriding.co.uk/news/Hull-s-young-drunks-TV-tonight-BBC-screens-Lock/article-3184546-detail/article.html|archivedate=14 February 2011|url-status=dead|newspaper=[[Hull Daily Mail]]|accessdate=13 November 2012}}</ref> consisting of 8 episodes where cameras rolled 24/7; the second series was aired primarily on the main [[BBC]] Channel, [[BBC One]].\n\n===''Neighbourhood Blues''===\nHumberside Police have also participated in the second series of ''Neighbourhood Blues'', that covered the work of the forces Neighbourhood Policing Teams. This was aired on weekday mornings for two weeks starting on 12 December 2012, on [[BBC One]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01nzlxh/episodes/guide#b01nzly0|title=Episode guide|work=Neighbourhood Blues|publisher=BBC|accessdate=13 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Officers killed in the line of duty==\n{{see also|List of British police officers killed in the line of duty}}\nThe [[Police Memorial Trust]] lists and commemorates all British police officers killed in the line of duty, and since its establishment in 1984 has erected over 38 memorials to some of those officers.\n\nSince the formation of Humberside Police six officers have been killed in the line of duty, these officers are:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.policememorial.org.uk/index.php?page=humberside-police|title=Humberside Police \u2013 Police Memorial Roll of Honour|date=12 November 2012|accessdate=12 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.policerollofhonour.org.uk/forces/england/humberside/humberside_roll.htm?page=humberside-police|title=Humberside Police \u2013 Police Roll of Honour|date=14 October 2016|accessdate=20 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n* '''September 1979''' \u2013 Police Constable, Linton Andee Le Blanc, 19, Killed when his patrol car crashed when responding to a burglar alarm call\n* '''January 1998''' \u2013 Police Constable Steven Stimpson, 33, Accidentally killed when his traffic patrol car left the road and crashed\n* '''August 1998''' \u2013 Police Constable James Heaton, 30, Fatally injured when his traffic car crashed when responding to an accident\n* '''September 1998''' \u2013 Police Constable Jonathan Templeton, 37, Collapsed and died of heart failure whilst on duty at [[Hedon]] Police Station.\n* '''July 2003''' \u2013 Police Constable Robert Douglas, 44, Killed in a road traffic accident returning from his duties at the airport\n* '''April 2015''' \u2013 Police Constable Russell Wylie, 28, During the morning of Monday 13 April 2015 he was on routine motorcycle patrol when he was involved in a collision with a car on the B1362, [[Burstwick]], East Riding of Yorkshire. He was airlifted to Hull Royal Infirmary, however his injuries proved to be fatal. He was a Traffic Officer based at Melton.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/police-officer-was-on-wrong-side-of-road-when-he-crashed-into-car-on-his-motorbike-1-7433653|title=Police officer 'was on wrong side of road' when he crashed into car on his motorbike|date=28 August 2015|work=Yorkshire Post|accessdate=20 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notable incidents and investigations==\nNotable major incidents and investigations in which Humberside Police have been involved in include:\n\n*'''August 2011: [[2011 England Riots]]:''' Specially trained officers were sent to assist the [[Metropolitan Police]] as riots broke out across the London area, which later spread across the country. under the command of ACC Stuart Donald, who was the senior force Chief officer, responsible for the deployment and co-ordination of operations in relation to the riots. Over 50 officers travelled to London to assist the Met Police.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisishullandeastriding.co.uk/Specially-trained-officers-Humberside-Police/story-13096862-detail/story.html|title=Humberside Police assist the Metropolitan Police with Riots|date=9 August 2011|work=This is Hull and East Riding|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505055951/http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/Specially-trained-officers-Humberside-Police/story-13096862-detail/story.html|archivedate=5 May 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref>\n*'''July 2010: [[2010 Northumbria Police manhunt|Northumbria Police Manhunt]]:''' Humberside Police was involved in the Major Police manhunt for [[Raoul Moat]] who, upon release from prison, shot his ex-girlfriend's new partner, his ex-girlfriend and the then serving Traffic Police Officer, PC [[David Rathband]]. Humberside Police, along with other police forces, provided mutual aid to [[Northumbria Police]] by providing armed police officer to assist in the armed police coverage and search for Raoul Moat.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/onetenth-of-uks-armed-police-join-in-manhunt-for-raoul-moat-2021220.html|title=One Tenth of UK Armed Police join manhunt from Roul Moat|date= 8 July 2010 | location=London|work=The Independent|first=Jonathan|last=Brown|accessdate=13 November 2012}}</ref>\n*'''February 2019:''' Disappearance of Libby Squire: On 1 February 2019 Humberside police launched a major search for missing Hull University student Libby Squire. Appeals were made on social media and a large police presence was focused around the Beverley Road area of Hull. Humberside Police arrested a man on suspicion of abduction a few days later and charged him with several unrelated offences. He was released under investigation in connection to Libby Squire. 7 weeks later, the body of Libby Squire was discovered in the Humber Estuary, over 30 miles from her last known location in Hull.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-47667840|title=Libby Squire: Tributes to Hull student after body found|date=22 March 2019|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref> On 24 October 2019, police charged 25 year old Pawel Relowicz for the rape and murder of Libby Squire.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-50169328|title=Libby Squire: Pawel Relowicz charged with murder and rape|date=24 October 2019|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Law enforcement in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[List of law enforcement agencies in the United Kingdom]]\n*[[Table of police forces in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Humberside Police}}{{Commons category|Emergency services in Lincolnshire}}\n*[http://www.humberside.police.uk/ Humberside Police]\n*[http://www.humberside-pa.org.uk/ Humberside Police Authority]\n*[http://www.humberside-pcc.gov.uk/Home.aspx Humberside Police Crime Commissioner]\n*[http://www.npas.police.uk/ National Police Air Service]\n\n{{UK home nations police forces}}\n\n[[Category:Organisations based in Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in the East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Police forces of England]]\n[[Category:1974 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1974]]\n[[Category:Humberside]]\n[[Category:Humberside Police| ]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "bray", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Humberside_Police"}
